{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0708538c-f186-49d0-a56e-7709c5dc57a1","content":"With **MSTest 3.8.2**, the modern approach is:\n\n1. **Constructor-inject `TestContext`** (replaces the old static property pattern)\n2. **Use `async Task` on `[TestInitialize]`** for both sync and async setup\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n    }\n\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task Setup()\n    {\n        // Synchronous work\n        var config = LoadConfig();\n\n        // Asynchronous work\n        await InitializeDatabaseAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task Cleanup()\n    {\n        await ReleaseDatabaseAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        TestContext.WriteLine(\"Logging from test\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` is the MSTest v3 way — no need for the old `public static TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` pattern.\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `async Task`, so put both sync and async work in one method.\n- You can only have **one** `[TestInitialize]` per class — combine all setup there.\n- For class-level (one-time) async setup, `[ClassInitialize]` also supports `async Task`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3d32f93d-2f00-4160-87a0-3bc8488774f4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In MSTest v3, the recommended modern approach uses:\n\n1. **`TestContext`** — injected via constructor (no more static property pattern).\n2. **`[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]`** — for class-level setup/teardown (static methods).\n3. **`[TestInitialize]` / `[TestCleanup]`** — for per-test setup/teardown.\n4. For async initialization, MSTest v3 supports `async Task` on `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]`.\n\n\n5. MSTest 3.x also supports constructor injection of `TestContext` and implementing `IAsyncDisposable` or `IDisposable` for resource cleanup, which is the most modern pattern.\n\nWriting test class example... I see the recommended pattern uses a single `[TestInitialize]` method with an `async Task` return type that handles both synchronous and asynchronous setup work, and similarly for cleanup. Constructor injection with TestContext is the modern MSTest 3.x approach replacing the old static property pattern.","outputTokens":1010},"id":"06679a29-90d5-4680-a1e4-5cd8914bee35","timestamp":"2026-04-05T02:02:02.736Z","parentId":"4ccc7d3e-25e1-4486-8961-0bfadb28a432"}
